        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 15189] Copying a Graphics Window Copies All Graphic Elements Rather Than Bitmap*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=15189>\n\nSimon Urbanek (<mailto:simon.urbanek@r-project.org|simon.urbanek@r-project.org>) changed:\n\n           What    |Removed                     |Added\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n             Status|NEW                         |CLOSED\n         Resolution|---                         |WISHLIST\n\n--- Comment #3 from Simon Urbanek (<mailto:simon.urbanek@r-project.org|simon.urbanek@r-project.org>) ---\nGood necromancy here, Kevin :).\n\nThis is very much as intended - bitmaps have terrible loss of quality which is\nwhy they are avoided - except in very special cases (like scatterplots of\nmillions of points, but there are better alternatives in that case). Windows\nuses bitmaps, because it has (had?) no native support for PDFs which are\nlossless, but macOS does (which is why is has so much higher quality of\noutput).\n\nNote that you can create a bitmap snapshot from the current window simply with \n```quartz.save(\"plot.png\")```\nif that is desired.\n\nIt would be possible to add an additional menu item - something like \"Copy as\nBitmap\", but for bitmaps to be useful they may require additional parameters\nsuch as setting the resolution (`dpi=` argument in `quartz.save` above)\ndepending on the purpose of the snapshot. I'll keep it on the wish list since\nthis is not a bug but rather a marginal feature request.",
